05643nam a22007455i 9780812296280DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122962807 a10.9783/97808122962802doi  a(DE-B1597)531796  a(OCoLC)1143793046  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0370102bisacsh1 aBaldwin, John W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKnights, Lords, and Ladies :bIn Search of Aristocrats in the Paris Region, 1180-1220 /cJohn W. Baldwin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b39 color, 35 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tForeword -- tAbbreviations and Short Titles -- tChapter 1. In Search of Aristocrats -- tChapter 2. Who’s Who -- tChapter 3. Family -- tChapter 4. Aristocratic Castles and Residences -- tChapter 5. Fiefs and Homage: The Nomina militum and Scripta de feodis -- tChapter 6. The Landed Wealth of Lay Aristocrats -- tChapter 7. The Landed Wealth of Churches and Monasteries -- tChapter 8. The Kingdom of Heaven -- tChapter 9. The Voice of Vernacular French -- tChapter 10. Knights at the Cathedral of Chartres -- tAppendix 1. Tables -- tAppendix 2. Genealogies -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the beginning of the twelfth century, the region around Paris had a reputation for being the land of unruly aristocrats. Entrenched within their castles, the nobles were viewed as quarrelling among themselves, terrorizing the countryside, harassing churchmen and peasants, pillaging, and committing unspeakable atrocities. By the end of the century, during the reign of Philip Augustus, the situation was dramatically different. The king had created the principal governmental organs of the Capetian monarchy and replaced the feudal magnates at the royal court with loyal men of lesser rank. The major castles had been subdued and peace reigned throughout the countryside. The aristocratic families remain the same, but no longer brigands, they had now been recruited for royal service.In his final book, the distinguished historian John Baldwin turned to church charters, royal inventories of fiefs and vassals, aristocratic seals and documents, vernacular texts, and archaeological evidence to create a detailed picture of the transformation of aristocratic life in the areas around Paris during the four decades of Philip Augustus's reign. Working outward from the reconstructed biographies of seventy-five individuals from thirty-three noble families, Baldwin offers a rich description of their domestic lives, their horses and war gear, their tourneys and crusades, their romantic fantasies, and their penances and apprehensions about final judgment.Knights, Lords, and Ladies argues that the aristocrats who inhabited the region of Paris over the turn of the twelfth century were important not only because they contributed to Philip Augustus's increase of royal power and because they contributed to the wealth of churches and monasteries but also for their own establishment as an elite and powerful social class.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.1 aJordan, William Chester, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordan, William Chester.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of